<p>I'm using <code>TimeZone.java</code> <code>getDisplayName()</code> to get display name for default time zone which would return "Indian Standard Time".</p>  <p>I tried this and working fine in Windows 7 OS. But when I tried the same in Mac OS X (Snow Leopard), the output is not as expected.</p>  <p>Code snippet:</p>  <pre><code>System.out.println("Time Zone is "+Calendar.getInstance().getTimeZone().getDisplayName(false,TimeZone.LONG)); </code></pre>  <p>Output in Windows:  <code>Time Zone is Indian Standard Time</code></p>  <p>Output in Mac: <code>Time Zone is GMT+05:30</code></p>  <p>Is there any other method to get the display name of default time zone that will work in any environment.</p>  <p>Note: I used Eclipse IDE (Version not sure) for Windows and NetBeans 6.9.1 IDE for mac. Will it make any difference?</p>